Project Goals

Following 2010 Haiti Earthquake link it was known that the people whose homes had been destroyed by the earthquake were creating temporary shelters using blue tarps, and these blue tarps would be good indicators of where the displaced persons were if only they could be located in time, out of the thousands of images that would be collected every day. The problem was that there was no way for aid workers to search the thousands of images in time to find the tarps and communicate the locations back to the rescue workers on the ground in time. The solution would be provided by data-mining algorithms, which could search the images far faster and more thoroughly (and accurately?) then humanly possible. The goal was to find an algorithm that could effectively search the images in order to locate displaced persons and communicate those locations rescue workers so they could help those who needed it in time.

The goal of this project is therefore to Use data from the actual data collection process was carried out over Haiti and test each of the algorithms you learn in this course on the imagery data collected during the relief efforts made Haiti in response to the 2010 earthquake, and determine which method you will use to as accurately as possible, and in as timely a manner as possible, locate as many of the displaced persons identified in the imagery data so that they can be provided food and water before their situations become unsurvivable.

Objective: Use Modeling Techniques with K-Folds and Test Results Against Various Thresholds

  1. provide a thresholds used
  2. explain and justify rationale

Step 0. Interpret the Problem Statement

In this classification problem, peoples lives are at stake. I want tests to be as accurate as possible and I want the relief delivery to be as efficient as possible. The latter part of that statement is important, because if time were no object, I could err on the side of delivering all of the resources (which are probably also finite) to everyone whether they needed them or not. But that isnt the case.

In other words, in addition to high recall, I also need to look at specificity to some degree. So this becomes a threshold problem where I am focused on both accuracy (true blue tarps divided by population) and precision (reducing false discovery; non-blue tarps). Looking at this tradeoff in terms of finding a meaningful diagnostic or score will be the way I will approach setting my threshold in Step 7.

Assumptions and Other Thoughts

I am making a few assumptions in this analysis. The first is that I have independent and identically distributed error terms in the data. Were using a dataset which sheds limited light on the methods of data collection other than it is high-resolution geo-referenced imagery. So I also need to assume the imagery data is very reliable in terms of how it has read the pixels and created unique and uniquely indexed plots. Another is that I dont know the distributions of the data well enough to decide on one parametric estimation technique.

Step 4. Validate Subset Selection Using Regularization

The results from my selection methods should be taken with a grain of salt. They have not been improved by using ridge/lasso with a training dataset and k-folds. I will try this method below.

set.seed(9)

# https://www.datacareer.ch/blog/ridge-and-lasso-in-r/
ridgeCV <- caret::train(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train,
                        method="glmnet", 
             tuneGrid=data.frame(alpha=rep(0,100), #for alpha = 0 to 100
                                 lambda=10^seq(4,0,length=100)), #select 100 values of lambda from 10^4 to 10^0
             trControl=trainControl("cv", number=10, returnResamp='all')) #k=5 folds cross validation
coef(ridgeCV$finalModel, ridgeCV$bestTune$lambda) %>% length() #it has all coefficients
#> [1] 6

lassoCV1 <- caret::train(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train,
                        method="glmnet", 
             tuneGrid=data.frame(alpha=rep(1,100), 
                                 lambda=10^seq(4,-2,length=100)),
             trControl=trainControl("cv", number=10, returnResamp='all'))
coef(lassoCV1$finalModel, lassoCV1$bestTune$lambda) %>% length() #it has all coefficients
#> [1] 6

In both of these methods, the final model has 6 coefficients, which means all 4 plus the intercept and response. So, this seems like a good model to proceed with.

Step 6. Tune Models by Varying the Thresholds

My threshold at the beginning of step 6 was set arbitrarily, and I made it a lower value (probability of non-tarp is high) because I knew I wanted high recall. But I am getting some false positives. I need to make a determination based on my underlying assumption at the beginning that sensitivity is more important - how much more important? The question I am essentially asking is how much more valuable is reducing the likelihood that I deliver to the wrong person than reducing the likelihood that I miss someone? If we assume that this trade-off can be represented as a fraction, I would recommend with 5 to 1. Here is how I derived this:

There are 2,022 tarps. The earthquake covered some 70 miles in diameter link. For one person to travel 70 miles (considering there is devastation, all-terrain vehicles may be necessary), this may take around 5 hours. If someone in a temporary shelter (blue tarp) was not actually injured, we may have lost 5 hours providing relief to someone who actually was injured, 70 miles away. I arrived at a fraction of 1 hours vs.these 5 hours by assuming it takes an hour on average for rescue workers to locate true positives from where they are dropped (probably close by, by helicopter).

In reality, I dont know anyones condition or the quality of other ground intelligence, so trying to layer in too many more assumptions about collective safety and security on the island is an overwhelmingly difficult task.

So, the high-sensitivity model (using best performer logistic regression) has shown me that about 1,000 of 1,600 people receive relief when my threshold is 0.99. In thinking about how much I can allow this to vary based on the answer above, I can assume I am saving. I decided to use a variance of the F1 score (the harmonic mean of precision and recall link, a more general F score to plug in my weighting. The equation is \(F=(1+)^2*(precision*recall)/(^2*precision)+recall\)

In my case, beta is 5, so the equation is coded below:

# Sensitivity: TP/(TP+FN)
# 1-Specificity: FP/(TN+FP)
set.seed(11)
thresholdinglog <- function(threshold){
  glm.fits<-glm(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train,family=binomial) 
  glm.fits %>% tidy()
glm.fits %>% augment() %>%
  mutate(.predicted_probability = inverse_logit(.fitted)) %>% 
  dplyr::select(.fitted, .predicted_probability) 

glm.logOdds_predictions <- glm.fits %>% augment(newdata=haiti_holdout) %>% 
  dplyr::select(binary, .fitted)  %>% 
  mutate(.prediction=ifelse(.fitted>threshold, "NonTarp", "Blue.Tarp")) %>%
  mutate(.prediction=fct_relevel(as_factor(.prediction), c("NonTarp", "Blue.Tarp"))) 
confmat<-caret::confusionMatrix(glm.logOdds_predictions$.prediction,as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp",mode="everything")
confmat
score<-(sensitivity/specificity)*(5/1)
base::paste(score,threshold)
}

thresholdinglda <- function(threshold){
glm.fit <- caret::train(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train, method="lda", 
              preProcess=c("center","scale"), 
              trControl = caret::trainControl("cv", number=10, #k-folds cross-validation
                          returnResamp='all', savePredictions='final',
                          classProbs=TRUE))
  glm.predictions <- predict(glm.fit, haiti_holdout, type="prob")
  glm.predictions <-glm.predictions %>% mutate(.prediction=ifelse(glm.predictions$NonTarp>threshold, "NonTarp", "Blue.Tarp"))

confmat<-caret::confusionMatrix(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp",mode="everything")
specificity<-caret::specificity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[2])
sensitivity<-caret::sensitivity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[1])

score<-(sensitivity/specificity)*(5/1)
base::paste(score,threshold)
}

thresholdingqda <- function(threshold){
glm.fit <- caret::train(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train, method="qda", 
              preProcess=c("center","scale"), 
              trControl = caret::trainControl("cv", number=10, #k-folds cross-validation
                          returnResamp='all', savePredictions='final',
                          classProbs=TRUE))
  glm.predictions <- predict(glm.fit, haiti_holdout, type="prob")
  glm.predictions <-glm.predictions %>% mutate(.prediction=ifelse(glm.predictions$NonTarp>threshold, "NonTarp", "Blue.Tarp"))

confmat<-caret::confusionMatrix(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp",mode="everything")
specificity<-caret::specificity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[2])
sensitivity<-caret::sensitivity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[1])

score<-(sensitivity/specificity)*(5/1)
base::paste(score,threshold)
}

thresholdingknn <- function(threshold){
glm.fit <- caret::train(binary~Green+Blue+Red*Green+Green*Blue, data=haiti.train, method="knn", 
              preProcess=c("center","scale"), 
              tuneGrid=data.frame(k=16),
              trControl = caret::trainControl("cv", number=10, #k-folds cross-validation
                          returnResamp='all', savePredictions='final',
                          classProbs=TRUE))
  glm.predictions <- predict(glm.fit, haiti_holdout, type="prob")
  glm.predictions <-glm.predictions %>% mutate(.prediction=ifelse(glm.predictions$NonTarp>threshold, "NonTarp", "Blue.Tarp"))

  confmat<-caret::confusionMatrix(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp",mode="everything")
specificity<-caret::specificity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[2])
sensitivity<-caret::sensitivity(as.factor(glm.predictions$.prediction),as.factor(haiti_holdout$binary),positive="NonTarp"[1])

score<-(sensitivity/specificity)*(5/1)
base::paste(score,threshold)
}

Conclusions

Which algorithm works the best?

The logistic regression is the front-runner. On the larger training set it performs the best even at the best threshold compared to other methods. Any tarp left behind is unacceptable, and KNN leaves 62 behind. However, KNN also rarely ever makes a false discovery, which makes it a close second to logistic regression. QDA seems to perform poorly, but also has the highest area under the curve (slightly better than logistic regression).

Method KNN(k=16) LDA QDA Logistic Regression
Accuracy 0.995 0.9905 0.9968 0.9961
AUC 0.99857 0.998 0.999 0.99857
ROC - - - -
Threshold 0.01 0.01 0.01 0.1
Sensitivity/Recall/Power 0.9999 0.9996 0.9984 0.9975
Specificity (1-FPR) 0.8491 0.7202 0.9465 0.9538
FDR 0.003 0.017 0.048 0.07
Precision (PPV) 0.9950 0.9907 0.9982 0.9984

Do these data seem particularly well-suited to one class of prediction methods, and if so, why?

In module 3.3 of the SYS 6018 course, we compared classification methods K-Nearest Neighbors, Linear Discriminant Analysis, and Quadratic Discriminant Analysis. According to the text, the best performing algorithm will usually be the one whose assumptions best match the data, and that performance will be poor if the model makes assumptions that are not represented in the data. Logistic regression assumes that log-odds (an expression of probability of an event occurring relative to not occurring) of the predictors are useful. KNN offers flexible parameters as it makes no assumptions. LDA and QDA assume that all classes have Gaussian distributions.

The data seem like they would be well suited to linear discriminant analysis, because there should be a clear linear boundary between complementary color classes (not quadratic) and they should have Gaussian distributions given their real world frequency. However, we can see below that is not clear from this dataset that all of the predictors have the same covariance.

cov(haiti$Blue,haiti$Green)
#> [1] 4302.854
cov(haiti$Red,haiti$Green)
#> [1] 5624.511
cov(haiti$Red,haiti$Blue)
#> [1] 4530.342

I believe this is the result of unequal representation of red, green, and blue pixels in the imagery, skewed away from blue. This makes it easier to describe the response variable as a binary one, making it a binary classification problem, and either logistic regression or knn are very well suited for that. I believe either method will generally perform very well, but knn might do better with a more diverse dataset, making LR the front-runner.

Are there additional recommend actions that might be taken to improve results?

One item that crossed my mind at the beginning of the effort is whether binary logistic regression is appropriate given that we have more than just binary data. I understand from online reading that multinomial logistic regression is a technique which can be used for clearer modeling between 3 or more classes. I think this could help us understand other structures a little better. The decision boundary could also be visualized on a plot across all classes (like it was in Module 3), to clearly show how confident we are at each class boundary in any of our methods (that was a powerful tool that I tried to find some code to mimic but it was taking a very long time even to test).

Additionally, dimension reduction techniques like principal components analysis could help with finding even better likelihoods when predicting new observations. I am not as equipped at what to do with the principal components model, i.e., how to plug it back in for testing and interpret the components, but I know we can compute it using the following technique:

set.seed(2)
#http://www.sthda.com/english/articles/37-model-selection-essentials-in-r/152-principal-component-and-partial-least-squares-regression-essentials/
#https://rstudio-pubs-static.s3.amazonaws.com/579414_4aea8984cf1d47abac389fde7eb6d24d.html
library(pls)
pcr.fits <- pcr(Class~., data=haiti.train,scale=TRUE,validation="CV")

And this analysis could be repeated in a Bayesian-statistics manner, which I am a lot less qualified to discuss. But given that there is probably a trove of imagery data to draw from given previous emergency relief efforts, we might have prior probabilities of the types of objects that we are classifying (soil, for example, should be quite common). Those might be considered by our model. This strikes me as especially important, because disasters of this scale do not occur everyday.

In addition, more GIS data to describe distance (in miles or km) of the false negatives to the nearest true positive would be useful. Since homes tend to be clustered in neighborhoods, this seems possible and it definitely would have improved my ability to estimate furthest distance between tarps better for my F-score, turning this into a shortest-path type of problem.
